fr:mainmatter.fr:tex:
\mathcal {L}_{M}{\mathopen {}\left (q,S,q'\right )\mathclose {}} =
{\mathopen {}\left \{u \in \Sigma _M^\star \,\middle \vert \,
  q \mathrel {\vphantom {\xrightarrow {u}}\smash {\xrightarrow {u}}^*}
q'
  \text { with all intermediate states lying in S}
\right \}\mathclose {}}

html:ol.html:li:
If we do pass through q_0, we must first go from q to q_0 without passing through q_0, then we return to q_0 arbitrarily many times, and then we finally go from q_0 to q without passing through q_0. This corresponds to the following concatenation of languages, which we know to be regular by our induction hypothesis and the fact that regular languages are closed under concatenation and repetition:

    \mathcal {L}_{M}{\mathopen {}\left (q,S',q_0\right )\mathclose {}}
    \mathcal {L}_{M}{\mathopen {}\left (q_0,S',q_0\right )\mathclose {}}^\star 
    \mathcal {L}_{M}{\mathopen {}\left (q_0,S',q'\right )\mathclose {}}

